  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1622891479" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1622891479" />
    <a title="Katie Ziegler (Life Between Words)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17825291-katie-ziegler-life-between-words"><img alt="Katie Ziegler (Life Between Words)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1434161411p2/17825291.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1622891479?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katie Ziegler (Life Between Words)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katie Ziegler (Life Between Words)" href="/user/show/17825291-katie-ziegler-life-between-words">Katie Ziegler (Life Between Words)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17825291-katie-ziegler-life-between-words?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1622891479" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1540910474910005521">Incredibly powerful and heartbreaking account.<br/><br/>Columbine was a landmark moment in my life. I was a freshman in highschool - at least several states away - when it happened, and it was earth shattering. I remember coming home from school, my mom folding laundry downstairs, eyes glued to the tv. Mine became glued as well. I remember the following days and weeks, the media frenzy, the harrowing first person accounts, the lives of the killers and victims dissected. Many of the early things that were </span>
  <span id="freeText1540910474910005521" style="display:none">Incredibly powerful and heartbreaking account.<br /><br />Columbine was a landmark moment in my life. I was a freshman in highschool - at least several states away - when it happened, and it was earth shattering. I remember coming home from school, my mom folding laundry downstairs, eyes glued to the tv. Mine became glued as well. I remember the following days and weeks, the media frenzy, the harrowing first person accounts, the lives of the killers and victims dissected. Many of the early things that were reported ended up being misrepresented or false, but of course I didn't know that at the time. I remember going to school and being fearful of the kids who wore trench coats. I mean, really. That's how insane that time was. But, it's also why I wanted to read this book. There are a few big events during my childhood and adolescence in which I remember exactly where I was when I heard - Baby Jenny falling down the well (I was like 3, so maybe I don't remember where I was when I heard, but I definitely remember it happening), Princess Diana's death, Columbine, and 9/11.<br /><br />At the time, I viewed the tragedy from the lens of a highschooler. Now, almost 20 years later, I view it as an adult and a parent. My heart breaks and grieves for Sue Klebold (and obviously the parents of the victims). This quote, towards the end of the book really struck me, "If I had thought there was something seriously wrong with [Dylan], I would have moved mountains to fix it. If I had known about Eric's website or the guns, or about Dylan's depression, I would have parented differently. As it was, I parented the best way I knew to parent the child I knew -- not the one he had become without my knowledge." As parents, we are constantly going where angels fear to tread; we want our children to grow into conscientious, respectful, kind human beings. That is a huge and daunting responsibility. We use the only resources that we have available to do the very best we can with the child that we know. So many of us want to say, and find comfort in saying, "that would never happen to me. I know my child." It's why there was (and almost always is) so much blame put on the parents of killers. We want to see ourselves as more aware and in tune and perceptive. I cannot imagine withstanding the kind of blame that was put on Sue and Tom (and Eric Harris's parents, too) - it is crushing for me to think about. <br /><br />One of the interesting things in Sue's reflection of Dylan, and observations about depression, is that his behavior leading up to the massacre, while concerning, didn't seem like red flags to her. Partly because the symptoms of depression in teenagers can often be masked by common teenage traits - sleeping long hours, irritability, and moodiness. What teenager doesn't display those things at one time or another? Even some of the more reckless and irresponsible things he did were not that unusual for teenagers to partake in. She never offers any excuses for what he did - just explanations and awareness. Her goal was to offer her perspective, what she went through, her love for her son, her utter desolation at what he did despite his upbringing, her grief for the victims, and awareness about suicide, and the very small subset of murder-suicide.<br /><br />Sue is remorseful to the point of flagellation at times; I can hardly blame her for that, but I did think some of the internal dialogue in which she questions "how could he have done this?" or "I couldn't understand how he could do this?" got a little repetitive. She is, understandably, so remorseful; And she has spent the last 15 years or so of her life repenting on behalf of Dylan and devoting herself to suicide prevention and awareness. In fact, all the proceeds from the book go towards just such a cause, which I think helps the case that this book was not written for the purpose of profiting off of tragedy (also, I am pretty convinced that no one reading this book could come away thinking that Sue is anything but a thoughtful, caring person).<br /><br />I am off the charts when it comes to empathy, so this book was hard for me to read. I imagine myself in her shoes. What if my sons, Fox or Wilder, ever did something like this? How would I cope? Not well, I think. Sue loves her son, to this day, but finds his actions reprehensible. I would love my boys, too. It's part and parcel with being a mom. She says at one point, "The world would have been better off if Dylan hadn't been born, but I wouldn't have." I get that. I get it. How, as a mother, can you reconcile your love for someone with the horrible things that they do? It's a tension I'm sure she'll live with for the rest of her life. <br /><br />As a side note, I'd be interested to read a book from Eric Harris's parents. I doubt we ever will - I have a feeling that would be an even more complicated book to write. <br /><br />Highly recommend this book. It's profound - and definitely shatters some of those preconceived notions a lot of people had about the Klebolds at the time of the massacre.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1540910474910005521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


